108
00:06:04.088 --> 00:06:04.868
So this is my

109
00:06:05.968 --> 00:06:07.028
disclosure statement.

110
00:06:08.528 --> 00:06:12.188
So in the lab, we are studying cancer aggressivity and in particular

111
00:06:12.248 --> 00:06:14.168
cancer metastasis, because

112
00:06:15.508 --> 00:06:19.428
actually cancer metastasis is the first reason of

113
00:06:19.628 --> 00:06:20.568
cancer mortality.

114
00:06:21.508 --> 00:06:24.088
When cancer are not metastasized, they are

115
00:06:25.508 --> 00:06:29.448
most often easily removable through surgery, but when they start to

116
00:06:29.488 --> 00:06:30.768
spread throughout the organism,

117
00:06:32.348 --> 00:06:36.128
there is no way for the surgery to fully eradicate the

118
00:06:36.168 --> 00:06:39.528
cancer. So that is why there is such intense research

119
00:06:39.608 --> 00:06:41.488
development about cancer metastasis.

120
00:06:41.928 --> 00:06:45.788
And one main reason about metastasis is the cancer cells'

121
00:06:45.868 --> 00:06:48.908
plasticity and most importantly, its dynamics.

122
00:06:49.238 --> 00:06:52.908
And you can see in these pictures of in vitro 41

123
00:06:52.948 --> 00:06:54.508
triple-negative breast cancer cells.

124
00:06:55.708 --> 00:06:59.308
You can see the acquisition of two different type of populations.

125
00:06:59.528 --> 00:07:02.928
One, a population of epithelial cells that do express

126
00:07:02.968 --> 00:07:06.728
E-cadherin. These cells as the cells that are

127
00:07:07.668 --> 00:07:11.368
required for the cancer proliferation, but also for the seeding at

128
00:07:11.388 --> 00:07:12.108
distant site.

129
00:07:13.348 --> 00:07:16.008
For instance, E-cadherin allows the cells to attach to each other.

130
00:07:16.228 --> 00:07:17.868
That's important for the primary tumor.

131
00:07:18.388 --> 00:07:22.068
That's also important for the cell seeding distantly, as the cells need to

132
00:07:22.148 --> 00:07:25.988
reattach. So on the early stage and the late stage of

133
00:07:26.088 --> 00:07:29.908
cancer, it's known that cancers must harbor such

134
00:07:30.028 --> 00:07:31.228
an epithelial phenotype.

135
00:07:32.068 --> 00:07:35.738
But on the same time, the cells are transitioning through different states,

136
00:07:35.828 --> 00:07:39.468
including the mesenchymal state, where cells are drastically changing

137
00:07:39.668 --> 00:07:43.328
their phenotype. And as you can see here, we start to express mesenchymal

138
00:07:43.368 --> 00:07:47.008
markers such as here the vimentin marker in green.

139
00:07:47.088 --> 00:07:50.908
So vimentin is a cytoskeleton molecule, and it allows the cancer cells

140
00:07:50.988 --> 00:07:54.268
to basically migrate and invade their surrounding environment.

141
00:07:54.738 --> 00:07:58.508
This is important for the cells to leave the primary tumor and escape

142
00:07:58.588 --> 00:08:00.348
and progress through

143
00:08:01.548 --> 00:08:02.768
the metastatic cascade.

144
00:08:03.578 --> 00:08:04.088
However,

145
00:08:04.968 --> 00:08:08.548
when the cell state is mesenchymal, they are vulnerable at some state of cancer

146
00:08:08.628 --> 00:08:12.528
progression. For instance, they will not do very well when they are

147
00:08:12.588 --> 00:08:16.448
circulatory tumor cells, and circulatory tumor cells does perform

148
00:08:16.508 --> 00:08:18.828
better as a cluster of cells. It's well known.

149
00:08:18.968 --> 00:08:22.948
And cluster of cells will engage epithelial molecules for the cells

150
00:08:23.018 --> 00:08:23.868
to attach together.

151
00:08:25.508 --> 00:08:29.057
So altogether, what we try is to understand the mechanism of this

152
00:08:29.068 --> 00:08:32.989
plasticity to block the cancer cell plasticity, thinking we can block

153
00:08:33.028 --> 00:08:36.889
metastasis. And we have tried in the lab to isolate these red cells

154
00:08:36.928 --> 00:08:39.788
versus green cells by single-cell isolation.

155
00:08:39.828 --> 00:08:43.369
But at the end, we keep regenerating cancer cells

156
00:08:43.408 --> 00:08:47.368
cultures from this isogenic population that are a mix of

157
00:08:47.468 --> 00:08:51.358
red and green. So which mean if we had a video of that pictures,

158
00:08:51.428 --> 00:08:53.828
you will see cells changing from red to green to red to--

159
00:08:54.688 --> 00:08:58.488
constantly changing between these two states, and we fail to stabilize these 10

160
00:08:58.497 --> 00:09:01.728
lines into a mesenchymal or epithelial type phenotype.

161
00:09:02.348 --> 00:09:06.308
However, in another model, which is an immortalized non-cancer model,

162
00:09:06.428 --> 00:09:09.968
which is the normal murine mammary gland cells, MMUMG,

163
00:09:10.668 --> 00:09:14.428
we saw at the very first passage from the ATCC

164
00:09:14.508 --> 00:09:18.188
that most of the cells are more like an epithelial phenotype, but some

165
00:09:18.248 --> 00:09:20.728
cells are more like a fibroblast-type phenotype.

166
00:09:21.098 --> 00:09:25.068
And we were able to isolate by single-cell seeding to generate two

167
00:09:25.168 --> 00:09:28.828
isogenic population. The epithelial phenotype was easy to

168
00:09:28.848 --> 00:09:32.768
obtain, as they represent 99.9% of the original

169
00:09:32.848 --> 00:09:36.808
cell population. And we were able to isolate some clones of the cells

170
00:09:36.848 --> 00:09:40.448
harboring this mesenchymal phenotype and having clones that are

171
00:09:40.528 --> 00:09:42.648
stable on this state, that are locked on the

172
00:09:42.688 --> 00:09:46.488
mesenchymal states. So we used

173
00:09:46.988 --> 00:09:48.688
this model, and basically we did

174
00:09:49.748 --> 00:09:53.628
transcriptional analysis. And when I did the gene ontology analysis

175
00:09:53.688 --> 00:09:57.497
for the genes that are differentially expressed between the mesenchymal and

176
00:09:57.848 --> 00:10:01.708
the epithelial phenotype on this isogenic model, so which means the

177
00:10:01.748 --> 00:10:03.528
cells have the same genetic background.

178
00:10:04.848 --> 00:10:08.648
So I had to scratch my head looking at the gene ontology because

179
00:10:08.728 --> 00:10:12.008
what came out was related to axon

180
00:10:12.888 --> 00:10:16.448
guidance molecules and memory loss and this type of biological

181
00:10:16.548 --> 00:10:20.228
process. And here we are talking about breast cancer cells in a Petri dish,

182
00:10:20.548 --> 00:10:23.338
not even on an animal. There is no neurons on the area.

183
00:10:23.868 --> 00:10:27.568
So I had to figure out what was going on with these mesenchymal cells

184
00:10:27.608 --> 00:10:31.028
expressing axon guidance molecules, neurons-related molecules.

185
00:10:31.828 --> 00:10:35.308
And actually, if you have a suspicion that your cells

186
00:10:35.368 --> 00:10:38.468
could modify the nervous system or

187
00:10:38.948 --> 00:10:40.508
interact with neurons,

188
00:10:41.328 --> 00:10:44.688
the simple assay you can do is the axonogenesis assay in vitro.

189
00:10:45.248 --> 00:10:48.968
Basically, you take the supernatant of your cells

190
00:10:49.348 --> 00:10:53.168
of interest, and you stimulate neuronal precursors,

191
00:10:53.238 --> 00:10:56.188
such as PC12 cells here with this supernatant.

192
00:10:56.578 --> 00:11:00.488
And as you can see, when I take the epithelial cell supernatant, there

193
00:11:00.548 --> 00:11:03.388
is not much reaction of the PC12 neuronal precursors.

194
00:11:03.848 --> 00:11:07.568
But when I subject these cells to the supernatant of

195
00:11:07.768 --> 00:11:11.318
mesenchymal cells, they start to differentiate and form more

196
00:11:11.328 --> 00:11:14.938
mature neural type of cells, which is actually because these

197
00:11:14.968 --> 00:11:18.668
mesenchymal cells express axon guidance molecules, which trigger the

198
00:11:18.688 --> 00:11:20.868
differentiation of these neuronal precursors.

199
00:11:21.568 --> 00:11:25.528
And in our specific case here, we were identifying

200
00:11:25.568 --> 00:11:29.188
the Semaphorin 4F as a major driver of this phenotype.

201
00:11:29.248 --> 00:11:32.848
And if you block Semaphorin 4F expression in the cancer cells,

202
00:11:33.348 --> 00:11:37.088
then the supernatants will not trigger this differentiation of

203
00:11:37.128 --> 00:11:40.938
neuronal precursors anymore. So it brought my research interest to the

204
00:11:41.008 --> 00:11:44.988
field of cancer neuroinvasion, and I started to think, wait, is there any neurons

205
00:11:45.108 --> 00:11:47.568
in cancer? At that time, it was not so obvious.

206
00:11:48.068 --> 00:11:52.008
So, and actually, if you get a xenograft of triple-negative breast

207
00:11:52.028 --> 00:11:55.828
cancer cells, you can see indeed here in green labeling the

208
00:11:55.868 --> 00:11:58.648
tubulin beta III has a pen neuronal marker.

209
00:11:59.008 --> 00:12:02.948
We can see the existence of nerve bundles here and nerve tweaks.

210
00:12:03.048 --> 00:12:06.868
Actually, nerve bundles are preexisting nerves that are invaded by cancer

211
00:12:06.908 --> 00:12:10.568
cells through the process of perineural invasion.The nerve twigs,

212
00:12:11.008 --> 00:12:14.928
that's an interesting aspect, is the generation of new nerves that are infiltrating

213
00:12:14.968 --> 00:12:15.948
throughout the tumor.

214
00:12:17.228 --> 00:12:20.828
And actually, the fact cancers can be innervated is not a new concept.

215
00:12:20.848 --> 00:12:24.708
It has been established in 1887, from my knowledge, the

216
00:12:24.748 --> 00:12:28.508
first demonstration of the presence of nerves into tumors by Dr. Young.

217
00:12:29.438 --> 00:12:33.348
And more recently, in 2001, Dr. Gustavo Hajela published

218
00:12:33.368 --> 00:12:37.308
this very seminal paper when he was the first to mix

219
00:12:37.368 --> 00:12:41.228
neuronal precursor cells, like neuronal cells

220
00:12:41.288 --> 00:12:43.708
from the dorsal root ganglia with prostate cancer cells.

221
00:12:43.758 --> 00:12:47.068
And what he saw is there is a directional

222
00:12:47.248 --> 00:12:48.788
communication between the

223
00:12:49.608 --> 00:12:52.828
neurons and the cancer cells, showing there is a nerve cancer and crosstalk which

224
00:12:52.868 --> 00:12:56.068
is occurring. And since then, the field of cancer

225
00:12:56.088 --> 00:12:59.868
innervation has been constantly growing, as you can see here

226
00:12:59.928 --> 00:13:02.828
on the PubMed entry related to the field.

227
00:13:03.328 --> 00:13:07.008
However, I want to put this in parallel with the field of cancer

228
00:13:07.048 --> 00:13:10.748
angiogenesis. And as you can see, cancer angiogenesis is in red, and we see the

229
00:13:10.828 --> 00:13:14.567
development after the Folkman demonstration and Folkman

230
00:13:14.628 --> 00:13:18.608
theory about angiogenesis. You can see in green, we still have a lot

231
00:13:18.648 --> 00:13:22.448
of room to grow in the field of cancer neuroscience, and that's very

232
00:13:22.908 --> 00:13:26.728
exciting. So please join the field if you have any idea in that direction.

233
00:13:28.048 --> 00:13:31.928
So what we have learned so far is there is a strong correlation between

234
00:13:31.948 --> 00:13:34.088
cancer innervation and the clinical outcome.

235
00:13:34.488 --> 00:13:36.368
More innervated cancer, higher nerve

236
00:13:37.248 --> 00:13:41.048
density, is usually associated to poor prognosis, especially to

237
00:13:41.228 --> 00:13:45.008
more metastasis. And in preclinical model, mostly

238
00:13:45.228 --> 00:13:49.048
mouse and rat, there is a clear association between nerve density and

239
00:13:49.148 --> 00:13:52.888
aggressive behaviors. Generally, when you denervate tumor,

240
00:13:53.068 --> 00:13:57.038
you have a less aggressive cancer, especially related to metastasis, but also

241
00:13:57.188 --> 00:14:01.048
to tumor growth. And more generally, the contribution of

242
00:14:01.308 --> 00:14:04.688
the nervous system on cancer behaviors is still a complex

243
00:14:04.708 --> 00:14:05.308
phenomenon.

244
00:14:06.308 --> 00:14:10.268
For instance, parasympathetic nerves can have different effect in different

245
00:14:10.278 --> 00:14:11.148
type of cancer.

246
00:14:12.188 --> 00:14:15.328
It's still something which is ongoing, and we are trying to elucidate.

247
00:14:15.368 --> 00:14:17.028
That's very exciting.

248
00:14:18.248 --> 00:14:22.088
So to go back to the research we are doing in the lab, so to recapitulate,

249
00:14:22.108 --> 00:14:26.048
what we demonstrate is the aggressive breast cancer cells, the mesenchymal

250
00:14:26.088 --> 00:14:29.348
type, that are activated for the epithelial-mesenchymal transition.

251
00:14:29.908 --> 00:14:33.188
We are secreting axon guidance molecules, such as the Semaforin 4F.

252
00:14:33.788 --> 00:14:37.628
And you can see this triggers a differentiation of neurons and a filtration where

253
00:14:37.668 --> 00:14:41.628
they come and extend axon and neurite and come in contact with cancer

254
00:14:41.648 --> 00:14:45.608
cells, as you can see here. The neurons is in green, and the cancer

255
00:14:45.628 --> 00:14:47.988
cells here are labeled, like the nuclei are labeled with DAPI.

256
00:14:48.488 --> 00:14:52.368
And you can see the existence of point of contact that suggests

257
00:14:52.388 --> 00:14:54.487
communication between neurons and cancer cells.

258
00:14:55.828 --> 00:14:59.088
And we wanted to validate this concept more on the in vivo setup,

259
00:14:59.368 --> 00:15:03.308
thinking that maybe we know that cancer plasticity is associated to

260
00:15:03.348 --> 00:15:07.248
metastasis. However, there is a big debate about how cancer metastasis

261
00:15:07.628 --> 00:15:09.808
is linked to this plasticity process.

