409
00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:52.660
And a reason for that is likely neurons are very long, and they are reaching out

410
00:23:52.720 --> 00:23:55.220
many cells. One neuron's going to reach hundreds of cells.

411
00:23:55.540 --> 00:23:58.980
So that may explain why there is such a prevalent transfer

412
00:23:59.860 --> 00:24:03.306
arising from the neurons.So we thought

413
00:24:03.316 --> 00:24:07.156
it's interesting and wanted to move forward to better understand

414
00:24:07.216 --> 00:24:10.696
what the biology behind it. And the problem with the strategy I was

415
00:24:10.716 --> 00:24:14.176
presenting to you earlier is with labeling the GFP with

416
00:24:14.216 --> 00:24:15.556
mitochondria, you

417
00:24:17.096 --> 00:24:20.676
cannot permanently mark recipient cells, and therefore you cannot follow the

418
00:24:20.756 --> 00:24:24.156
fate of the cells receiving mitochondria from any donor

419
00:24:24.316 --> 00:24:27.756
cells. And you cannot distinguish cells that never receive

420
00:24:27.776 --> 00:24:30.476
mitochondria versus those that receive mitochondria.

421
00:24:30.896 --> 00:24:34.635
In the sense that when the transfer occurs, the GFP signal will

422
00:24:34.696 --> 00:24:36.285
quickly disappear on the recipient cells.

423
00:24:36.536 --> 00:24:40.216
So that's a good way to document the transfer and to quantify the transfer at a

424
00:24:40.236 --> 00:24:42.696
given time, but not a good way for lineage tracing.

425
00:24:43.176 --> 00:24:46.176
So we designed MitoTracer basically in the donor cells.

426
00:24:46.476 --> 00:24:50.396
So this can work in any type of cells. We use that for neuron cancer transfer.

427
00:24:50.776 --> 00:24:54.256
And basically on the neuronal cells here, we overexpress a Cre

428
00:24:54.336 --> 00:24:57.816
recombinase, which is anchored to the mitochondria outer membrane,

429
00:24:58.576 --> 00:25:02.116
and this is separated by a TEV protease cleavage site.

430
00:25:02.386 --> 00:25:05.996
And on the recipient cells, we do have a classical mCherry to

431
00:25:06.096 --> 00:25:09.786
GFP Cre-Lox switch. So basically, the cells are constitutively

432
00:25:09.816 --> 00:25:12.936
expressing mCherry 304 until they are

433
00:25:13.436 --> 00:25:17.156
subjected to the Cre recombinase, and this Cre recombinase removes the mCherry

434
00:25:17.636 --> 00:25:19.276
and put the GFP in frame, and the cells are

435
00:25:20.456 --> 00:25:22.196
turning into permanently green cells.

436
00:25:23.176 --> 00:25:26.416
And one trick here is mitochondria never go to the nucleus.

437
00:25:27.076 --> 00:25:30.916
So the trick was to express the TEV protease by the recipient cells.

438
00:25:31.016 --> 00:25:34.716
So once the mitochondria come and are transferred to the recipient

439
00:25:34.756 --> 00:25:38.696
cells, the Cre is released by the TEV protease, and then

440
00:25:38.756 --> 00:25:42.246
it's going to the nucleus because there is an NLS on it, and you can activate the

441
00:25:42.296 --> 00:25:46.196
switch. And this is the type of video we can have on the time-lapse

442
00:25:46.236 --> 00:25:48.176
microscopy. You can see these red cancer cells.

443
00:25:48.256 --> 00:25:50.356
They are constitutively red, and when they are

444
00:25:52.276 --> 00:25:56.056
receiving mitochondria from the donor cells that are non-labeled, they turn

445
00:25:56.276 --> 00:26:00.136
into a green color, which is permanent. So that the MitoTracer technology.

446
00:26:01.236 --> 00:26:05.116
And basically, we can use this technology to backtrace the transfer.

447
00:26:05.576 --> 00:26:09.196
And here you can see the cells that are making these transitions that

448
00:26:09.236 --> 00:26:11.356
receive a neuronal mitochondrion.

449
00:26:11.796 --> 00:26:15.656
Those after they have established long tunneling nanotubes, between

450
00:26:15.716 --> 00:26:19.556
neurons and cancer cells, we actually demonstrated most of the transfer are

451
00:26:19.616 --> 00:26:20.696
occurring through that route.

452
00:26:21.636 --> 00:26:25.576
So together we use this strategy to understand the impact of the transfer

453
00:26:25.596 --> 00:26:29.236
of mitochondria into the cancer cell biology and especially

454
00:26:29.276 --> 00:26:32.846
metastasis. So basically, we took the nerve cancer co-cultures,

455
00:26:33.236 --> 00:26:37.076
injected into the mice, and as you can see here on the

456
00:26:37.096 --> 00:26:41.076
primary tumor, we observe 5 to 6% of cells having receiving

457
00:26:41.116 --> 00:26:41.816
mitochondria

458
00:26:42.756 --> 00:26:46.396
from the neurons. But when you looked on the metastatic

459
00:26:46.456 --> 00:26:50.056
sites, here is the lungs and the brain, we do see a strong

460
00:26:50.096 --> 00:26:53.756
enrichment to these green recipient cells, which does demonstrate that

461
00:26:53.956 --> 00:26:57.736
actually that these green cells that receive mitochondria into the primary tumor,

462
00:26:58.176 --> 00:27:01.796
they are more likely to perform metastasis and to succeed

463
00:27:01.856 --> 00:27:03.856
in forming distance metastasis.

464
00:27:04.916 --> 00:27:08.896
So basically, we try to understand a little bit about the mechanism beyond that,

465
00:27:09.616 --> 00:27:12.056
behind this increase in metastasis.

466
00:27:12.756 --> 00:27:16.196
A little disappointing when we isolated the red versus green cells,

467
00:27:16.696 --> 00:27:20.616
tested their invasive capacities in vitro in a Boyden chamber, and we did

468
00:27:20.656 --> 00:27:23.415
not see a difference in invasion on the cells.

469
00:27:23.976 --> 00:27:27.556
So I had to scratch my head again, but actually, we went back to the mice.

470
00:27:27.636 --> 00:27:31.356
We injected the red versus green, and we confirmed that, yes, the green cells are

471
00:27:31.376 --> 00:27:35.156
more metastatic. They are not invasive per se, but they are more metastatic.

472
00:27:35.656 --> 00:27:39.296
And actually, the metastatic process is a very complex

473
00:27:39.336 --> 00:27:42.956
multi-step cascade and is also very inefficient.

474
00:27:43.396 --> 00:27:47.376
So ultimately, 99.9% of metastatic cells

475
00:27:47.436 --> 00:27:51.396
will fail to form distance metastasis. There is many reason for that.

476
00:27:51.536 --> 00:27:54.916
For instance, oxidative stress and shear stress, which is obtained on the

477
00:27:54.956 --> 00:27:58.596
bloodstream, are main reason for metastatic cells to not

478
00:27:58.656 --> 00:28:02.496
survive. And actually, we tested the red versus green

479
00:28:02.536 --> 00:28:04.856
recipient cells for these metastatic stressors.

480
00:28:05.256 --> 00:28:08.956
And we confirmed that indeed, the green cells are more

481
00:28:08.996 --> 00:28:12.816
resisting to oxidative stress and are less dying when we

482
00:28:12.856 --> 00:28:16.496
give them physiological quantity of oxidative stress.

483
00:28:17.536 --> 00:28:20.855
And the same is true, we developed with this shear stress

484
00:28:21.336 --> 00:28:24.836
assay where we pass these cells through fine capillaries, about 10

485
00:28:24.876 --> 00:28:27.816
passages, and this tends to kill the cells because of the shear stress.

486
00:28:28.116 --> 00:28:31.766
And we see that in term of dying cells, the green cells,

487
00:28:32.196 --> 00:28:35.946
the recipient cells, are performing much better, so they can resist better to the

488
00:28:36.036 --> 00:28:36.596
shear stress.

489
00:28:37.416 --> 00:28:41.336
And so this will explain why we see more metastasis

490
00:28:41.396 --> 00:28:43.636
after the transfer of mitochondria into the cells.

491
00:28:43.956 --> 00:28:47.796
It's not invasive per se, and actually, it's bringing us to rethink

492
00:28:47.876 --> 00:28:51.776
the rates of metastasis and think how metastasis will occur and what

493
00:28:51.836 --> 00:28:54.676
we should target. Because for a long time, and still we

494
00:28:55.056 --> 00:28:58.656
keep trying to find the genes and the

495
00:28:58.716 --> 00:29:02.196
mechanism that produce invasive capacities in the cells.

496
00:29:02.236 --> 00:29:05.916
But as we can see, invasion metastasis is not only about

497
00:29:05.956 --> 00:29:09.876
invasion, and actually, there is 0.1% of the population

498
00:29:09.956 --> 00:29:13.796
that needs to be targeted. Every metastatic cell is invasive, but

499
00:29:13.816 --> 00:29:15.796
not every invasive cell is metastatic.

500
00:29:16.316 --> 00:29:20.156
And actually, we need to think more about metastatic cells

501
00:29:20.176 --> 00:29:23.916
being very well organized and networking cells.

502
00:29:24.276 --> 00:29:28.236
And when we can target this network or target this subset of cells

503
00:29:28.256 --> 00:29:31.956
that are efficient to survive during the process, we may make significant

